namics in the Music Career of Joan Trimble -- t11. Rhoda Coghill and the Gender Politics of Piano Performance -- tPart IV: Situating Discourses of Women, Gender and Music in the Twenty-First Century -- t12. Women and Composition: Fifty Years of Progress? -- t13. Transcending Conventional Habits: Music and the Collaborative Process in Joint Works -- t14. Surveying the Scene: Current Thoughts on Women and Electroacoustic Music in Ireland -- t15. We Buried the Heteropatriarchy and Danced on its Grave: Towards a Liberation Movement for Irish Traditional Music -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tIrish Musical Studies Previous volumes0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExplores the world of women's professional and amateur musical activity as it developed on and beyond the island of Ireland.In a story which spans several centuries, the book highlights representative composers and performers in classical music, Irish traditional music, and contemporary art music whose contributions have been marginalised in music narratives. As well as investigating the careers of public figures, this edited collection brings attention to women who engaged with and taught music in a variety of domestic settings. It also shines a spotlight on women who worked behind the scenes to build infrastructures such as festivals and educational institutions which remain at the heart of the country's musical life today. The book addresses and reconsiders ideas about the intersections of music, gender, and Irish society, including how the national emblem of the harp became recast as a symbol of Irish womanhood in the twentieth century. The book is divided into four parts. Part 1 surveys women musicians in Irish society of the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries. Part 2 discusses women and practice in Irish traditional music. Part 3 studies gaps and gender politics in the history of twentieth-century women composers and performers. Part 4 situates discourses of women, gender, and music in the twenty-first century. The book's contributors encompass musicologists, cultural historians, composers, and performers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMusiczIreland. 0aMusicianszIreland. 0aWomen musicianszIreland. 0aWomenzIreland. 4aModern History. 4aMusic. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Classical.2bisacsh  aClassical Music.  aComposers.  aContemporary Art Music.  aCultural Historians.  aGender Politics.  aHarp.  aIrish Society.  aIrish Traditional Music.  aMusicologists.  aPerformers.1 aBeausang, Ita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeausang, Ita, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aByrne Bodley, Lorraine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, Rhona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDignam, Barbara Jillian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngelhardt-Krajanek, Margarethe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKearney, Daithí, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlein, Axel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLawlor, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeFanu, Nicola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMullaney-Dignam, Karol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO'Donnell, Mary Louise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO'Donnell, Teresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’Connor-Madsen, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1